<topic id="customizing_an_existing_framework">
  <title>Customizing an Existing Framework</title>
  <body>
    <p>An existing framework for which Oxygen has default support (for example the <b>DITA</b>
      framework) can be extended and customized. Afterwards this customization can be shared with
      others: <xref href="http://blog.oxygenxml.com/2015/08/document-type-extension-sharing.html"
        format="html" scope="external"/>. You can use such a framework customization extension
      to:</p>
    <ul id="ul_fhj_1kk_rgb">
      <li>
        <p>Provide custom new file templates: <xref
            href="http://blog.oxygenxml.com/2015/12/sharing-new-custom-file-templates-for.html"
            format="html" scope="external"/></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Provide a custom CSS layer to render the framework in the <b>Author</b> visual editing
          mode: <xref href="http://blog.oxygenxml.com/2016/10/customizing-dita-visual-editing.html"
            format="html" scope="external"/></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Provide custom Schematron-based validation for the XML documents: <xref
            href="http://blog.oxygenxml.com/2017/02/sharing-schematron-validation-rules.html"
            format="html" scope="external"/></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Provide custom Author actions on the toolbar and in the contextual and main
          framework-specific menu: <xref
            href="http://blog.oxygenxml.com/2018/01/composing-author-actions.html" format="html"
            scope="external"/></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </body>
</topic>
